      "id": "ai-workload-fit",
      "type": "richTextBlock",
      "props": {
        "content": "# What Matters for RAG, Freshness, and Semantic Search Requirements\n\nWhen evaluating databases for retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) and semantic search workloads, three critical dimensions determine success:\n\n## Freshness & Update Frequency\n\n**RAG systems depend on current data.** If your embeddings index stale or out-of-sync source data, your LLM retrieves incorrect or outdated context, degrading answer quality and user trust. Key considerations:\n\n- **Write latency**: How quickly do updates propagate from your operational system to the vector index? Ideally sub-second to low-millisecond for real-time RAG.\n- **Consistency guarantees**: ACID transactions ensure that when you update a document's text *and* its embedding simultaneously, both reflect the same version. Without this, semantic search may retrieve \"correct\" embeddings for outdated source material.\n- **Refresh frequency**: Can you afford to rebuild or reindex embeddings on a schedule (hourly, daily), or do you need continuous incremental updates? Real-time analytics databases and distributed SQL databases with built-in vector search typically support both.\n- **Multi-source coherence**: If your RAG pipeline pulls from transactional databases, data warehouses, and external APIs, a unified platform (like an HTAP database) keeps all layers in sync more easily than splitting across separate vector databases and SQL systems.\n\n## Retrieval Quality & Semantic Search Precision\n\n**Quality depends on the distance metric, recall targets, and filtering accuracy.**\n\n- **Vector indexing & similarity algorithms**: Databases must support multiple distance metrics (cosine, Euclidean, dot product) and advanced indexing (HNSW, IVF, quantization) to balance recall@k performance and latency.\n- **Hybrid search**: Real-world RAG often needs both semantic (vector) and keyword (SQL) filtering—e.g., \"find documents about 'pricing' from 2025 by author 'Alice'.\" Systems that support SQL + vector in one query without cross-database hops (distributed SQL databases with vector search, NewSQL, or HTAP solutions) reduce latency and complexity.\n- **Metadata filtering**: Embeddings alone don't capture structured context. A robust retrieval engine must filter on SQL conditions (date ranges, user IDs, categories, tags) *during* or *before* vector search, not after. This dramatically improves recall precision and reduces false positives.\n- **Recall & precision tradeoffs**: Know your target recall@k (e.g., \"retrieve top-5 results with ≥90% recall\") and measure it with your dataset. Different vector databases and distance metrics yield different recall profiles; distributed SQL databases or cloud-native database options may trade some peak vector performance for operational flexibility and SQL semantics.\n\n## Practical Checklist for Your RAG Workload\n\n- **Dataset size & embedding dimensionality**: How many vectors? What dimension (e.g., 768 for small LLMs, 1536+ for GPT models)? This determines index strategy and whether a managed vector database, self-hosted embeddings database, or unified platform (like a distributed SQL database with vector search) fits your budget and latency targets.\n- **Write & update patterns**: Batch ingestion (once daily) or real-time streaming (sub-second)? This shapes freshness strategy and consistency guarantees you can afford.\n- **Filter selectivity**: Do 90% of your queries filter on structured metadata before vector search, or 10%? High-selectivity filtering favors SQL + vector integration (distributed SQL, HTAP, or MySQL-compatible databases with vector extensions).\n- **Latency SLA**: Is 100ms acceptable? 10ms? 1ms? Retrieval latency directly impacts user experience in chat, search, and recommendation features.\n- **Scale & operations**: Do you need Kubernetes-native deployment, multi-AZ failover, horizontal scaling SQL performance, or real-time analytics capabilities? This often tips the scale toward cloud-native databases (TiDB Cloud, cloud-managed services) over single-node or self-hosted vector databases.\n\n**Bottom line:** RAG and semantic search success hinges on keeping operational data, embeddings, and filters **consistent, fresh, and queryable together**. A unified platform—whether a distributed SQL database, HTAP database, or cloud-native system that combines SQL, ACID transactions, and vector search—eliminates sync bottlenecks and simplifies operations.",
        "maxWidth": "prose"
      },
      "style": {
        "background": "none",
        "spacing": "section"
      }
