      "id": "decision-framework",
      "type": "richTextBlock",
      "props": {
        "content": "# Which Database Should You Choose? (Decision Framework)\n\n## Understanding Your Requirements\n\nChoosing the right database for AI applications depends on how your architecture should be structured: **unified** (SQL + vector + ACID in one system) or **split** (separate transactional and vector databases).\n\nThis decision tree maps your core requirements to the right approach:\n\n### 1. **Do you need SQL filtering alongside vector search?**\n\n**Yes** → You likely need a unified or hybrid approach. Queries like \"find similar product embeddings WHERE category = 'electronics' AND price < $500\" require coordinated SQL and vector retrieval in a single transaction.\n\n- **TiDB** (Unified path): Combines distributed SQL with native vector search and ACID transactions. Eliminates cross-system joins and ensures consistency.\n- **PostgreSQL + pgvector**: SQL-first with vector extensions. Simple for prototypes; scaling vector search may require additional optimization.\n- **MongoDB Atlas + Vector Search**: Document-native with embedded vectors. Good if your operational data is already document-centric.\n\n**No** → A split stack (dedicated vector DB + transactional system) may be simpler.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **How critical is real-time consistency between transactional data and embeddings?**\n\n**Critical** (e.g., fraud detection, live recommendations, inventory-driven search):\n\n- **TiDB** provides ACID guarantees across SQL and vector operations, ensuring your RAG system never retrieves stale or inconsistent source material.\n- **CockroachDB** offers strong consistency across distributed nodes if global resilience is required alongside consistency.\n- **SingleStore** combines real-time transactional writes with fast analytical queries, useful when AI features depend on fresh operational metrics.\n\n**Acceptable lag** (e.g., overnight model retraining, batch inference):\n\n- **Pinecone**, **Weaviate**, or **Milvus** paired with any transactional database. Eventual consistency is acceptable; simpler operational model.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **What is your deployment constraint?**\n\n**Kubernetes-native required** (cloud-native platform, self-hosted, multi-region):\n\n- **TiDB** (via TiDB Operator): Production-grade Kubernetes support with built-in replication, monitoring, and cloud-native backup strategies. Unified SQL + vector in a Kubernetes database.\n- **CockroachDB**: Mature Kubernetes operator; strong multi-AZ resilience; vector search handled externally.\n- **PostgreSQL + pgvector**: Simple Kubernetes deployment via StatefulSets; moderate scaling complexity for vector workloads.\n\n**Managed cloud only** (minimize ops overhead):\n\n- **TiDB Cloud** (AWS, GCP, Azure): Fully managed distributed SQL + vector search + HTAP analytics. Zero infrastructure management.\n- **MongoDB Atlas**: Managed document database with vector search; scales vector operations automatically.\n- **Pinecone**, **Weaviate Cloud**: Fully managed vector-specific platforms; pair with managed transactional DB (e.g., Firebase, Neon, AWS RDS).\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Do you need real-time analytics on operational data?**\n\n**Yes** (e.g., dashboard queries, anomaly detection, operational reporting alongside RAG):\n\n- **TiDB** (HTAP database): Unified SQL + vector search + real-time analytics in one system. Execute OLTP writes and OLAP queries on the same data without ETL delay.\n- **SingleStore**: Optimized for fast aggregations and real-time dashboards with AI capabilities.\n\n**No** (pure transactional + vector retrieval):\n\n- Any of the unified or split-stack options above; HTAP capability is optional.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **What is your team's existing technology footprint?**\n\n**MySQL-heavy teams:**\n\n- **TiDB** is MySQL-compatible (drop-in replacement for many workloads) and adds distributed SQL, HTAP, and native vector search.\n- **PostgreSQL + pgvector**: Requires migration from MySQL; strong open-source ecosystem for embeddings.\n\n**MongoDB teams:**\n\n- **MongoDB Atlas + Vector Search**: Keeps you in the document-centric world; vector search is native.\n\n**Cloud-locked (AWS/GCP/Azure):**\n\n- **Google Cloud Spanner** (GCP): Managed distributed SQL; vector search via Vertex AI / external service.\n- **AWS DynamoDB + Aurora PostgreSQL + OpenSearch**: Multi-service approach; split stack common here.\n- **TiDB Cloud** on your preferred cloud: Unified option across all three major clouds.\n\n---\n\n## Decision Tree Summary\n\n```\nStart: What is your primary AI workload?\n\n├─ RAG + semantic search with SQL filtering required?\n│  ├─ YES + real-time consistency critical\n│  │  └─→ [UNIFIED] TiDB (Kubernetes) or TiDB Cloud (managed)\n│  │      → Reduces stack complexity, ensures consistency, supports HTAP analytics\n│  └─ YES + eventual consistency acceptable\n│     └─→ [HYBRID] PostgreSQL + pgvector + Pinecone/Milvus (split)\n│        → Simpler per-service scaling, familiar SQL layer\n│\n├─ Vector retrieval only (embeddings-first, no complex SQL joins)?\n│  └─→ [DEDICATED VECTOR] Pinecone, Weaviate, or Milvus\n│     + separate transactional system (MongoDB, PostgreSQL, etc.)\n│     → Purpose-built performance, simpler vector-only ops\n│\n└─ Real-time analytics + transactional + vector search?\n   └─→ [HTAP + UNIFIED] TiDB (with HTAP analytics)\n      → One system for OLTP writes, OLAP queries, and vector search\n```\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation Summary\n\n| **Your Priority** | **Recommended Path** | **Key Benefit** |\n|---|---|---|\n| Unified SQL + vector + consistency | **TiDB** | Single source of truth; no cross-system joins; ACID guarantees |\n| Kubernetes-native + distributed SQL | **TiDB Operator** | Production-ready; multi-region resilience; cloud-native |\n| Real-time analytics + transactions + AI | **TiDB (HTAP)** | OLTP, OLAP, and embeddings in one system; no ETL delay |\n| Managed, zero-ops, vector-first | **Pinecone + managed DB** | Simplest vector operations; separate concerns; easy scaling |\n| MySQL compatibility + scale-out | **TiDB** | Drop-in migration path; distributed SQL; vector search added |\n| Document-native + embedded vectors | **MongoDB Atlas** | Familiar document queries; vector search co-located |\n| Global resilience + strict consistency | **CockroachDB** (+ external vector DB) | Multi-region consensus; ACID; vector handled separately |\n\n---\n\n### Next Steps\n\n1. **Map your architecture**: Does your team need unified or split? Is Kubernetes a requirement?\n2. **Run a proof of concept**: [Try TiDB Cloud](https://www.pingcap.com/tidb/cloud/) for unified SQL + vector search, or evaluate Pinecone for vector-only workloads.\n3. **Benchmark your workload**: See the [Benchmarks section](#benchmarks) below for testing guidance.\n4. **Review integration guides**: Check [TiDB vector search for AI applications](https://www.pingcap.com/blog/integrating-vector-search-into-tidb-for-ai-applications/) or [Why distributed SQL databases for modern apps](https://www.pingcap.com/blog/why-distributed-sql-databases-elevate-modern-app-dev/) to understand integration depth.",
        "maxWidth": "prose"
      },
      "style": {
        "background": "none",
        "spacing": "section"
      }
